  "target_response": {
    "text": "They measure opposite ends of your heart's range, so they should be far apart. Your resting heart rate is 54 bpm — your heart at complete rest, sampled during sleep — and it's just under your 30-day average of 55.2 bpm, which is a good sign. The 151 bpm is your run's average working heart rate: what your heart did while you pushed for 44 minutes. Its peak of 176 bpm stayed below your estimated max of 190 bpm, so the run was hard but controlled. A big gap between resting and working heart rate is exactly what fitness looks like — the same pump idling low and revving high. Keep reading the morning number for recovery and the workout numbers for effort; neither replaces the other.",
